  "meta": {
    "title": "Hydrothermal vent: life without sunlight",
    "date": "2026-07-18",
    "lesson": "Kilometres below the sunlit sea, hydrothermal vents gush superheated fluid rich in hydrogen sulfide. No light reaches here, so the food web is built on chemosynthesis: chemolithoautotrophic bacteria such as Sulfurovum oxidize the sulfide to fix carbon, forming thick mats around the vent. You ARE such a cell — you do not chase particles; you draw energy directly from the sulfide plume. Stay in the warm chemical haze near the vent floor, because away from it there is nothing to live on.",
    "citation": "Dick (2019). The microbiomes of deep-sea hydrothermal vents. Nat Rev Microbiol. doi:10.1038/s41579-019-0160-2",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "realWorldBasis": "Deep-sea hydrothermal vent chemosynthetic community"
  },
